<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910318-0172</DOCNO><DOCID>910318-0172.</DOCID><HL>   Two Former Officials   Of Ponce Bank Agree   To Quit Industry</HL><DATE>03/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   PFBS AMRI SPC GDW</CO><IN>MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)BANKS (BNK)REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)WESTERN U.S. BANKS (BAW)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Two former officers of Ponce Federal Bank,Ponce, Puerto Rico, signed consent agreements banning themfrom the banking industry.   Separately, federal thrift regulators took control ofAmeriFirst Bank, the oldest federally charteredsavings-and-loan. The Miami-based institution had $3.7billion in assets and $2.8 billion in deposits. TheResolution Trust Corp., the Sandamp;L cleanup agency, will managethe thrift until it is sold or liquidated.</LP><TEXT>   In addition, the RTC transferred $874.3 million of insureddeposits of Security Savings andamp; Loan Association, Scottsdale,Ariz., to Security Pacific Bank Arizona, Phoenix, and WorldSavings andamp; Loan Association, Oakland, Calif. Security PacificBank Arizona is a unit of Security Pacific Corp., LosAngeles. World Savings is a subsidiary of Golden WestFinancial Corp., Oakland. Security Savings' 20 branches willreopen today as offices of Security Pacific and WorldSavings.   In the consent agreement with thrift regulators, Ramiro L.Colon Jr., former president and chairman of Ponce Federal,and Wendell Colon, former counsel to the savings bank, didn'tadmit any guilt, but they agreed to pay combined restitutionof $50,000, and Ramiro Colon agreed to repay a further $1million. They also relinquished the right to vote any sharesthat they hold in any bank or thrift.   The thrift office brought an enforcement action lastAugust against Ramiro and Wendell Colon and other boardmembers of the thrift, alleging insider transactionsincluding one that involved the purchase of 101 race horses.   Ramiro Colon's repayment includes $615,000 that the thriftpaid to him in August after the Office of Thrift Supervisioninformed the thrift that it intended to remove him from hispost.   The two men, whose phone numbers in Puerto Rico areunlisted, couldn't be reached for comment.</TEXT></DOC>